results.name: G.f. satisfies: [x^(n-1)] A(x)^(n^2) = (n!)^2 for n>=1.
comment: (3) ODD TERMS: It appears that for k>0, a(k) is odd iff k = 2*A003714(n)+1 for n>=0, where A003714 is the fibbinary numbers (integers whose binary representation contains no consecutive ones); this is true for at least the first 531 terms. [See also A171791 and A263075.]
Conjectures hold to at least a(1000). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 21 2015
link: Paul D. Hanna, Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..265
example: where the terms along the main diagonal begin:
Note that odd terms a(n) occur at positions n starting with:
which seems to equal A118113, the even fibbinary numbers + 1, with an initial zero included.
program: (PARI) {a(n) = local(A=[1, 1]); for(i=1, n+1, A=concat(A, 0); m=#A; A[m] = ( m!^2 - Vec(Ser(A)^(m^2))[m] )/m^2 ); A[n+1]}
